Really looks like we’re going to see a similar evolution to what happened in, e.g., 2009, 2013, or 2014 (bin #5). Also still credible—but less likely— is a more 2010/2008-like evolution (bin #4). Lower bins would require a unique trajectory not seen in the last few decades to take place going forward (no previous year would be analogous). I wouldn’t put it past Mother Nature to throw a curveball but it seems increasingly unlikely at this point.

Looking more carefully at the historical data, it seems that it is more common for years with very low max. sea ice (like 2022) to have a less extreme seasonal variation in thickness, with the change in thickness tending to “flatten out”, like in 2005, 2006. This expectation also seems to be much more consistent with how the crowd is forecasting.

Climate change isn’t a “reversion to the mean” kind of phenomenon. Initial highly subjective forecast, heavily influenced by the patterns of the last 2-3 years, and noting the marked longer term trend towards lower and lower sea ice extents.

Sea ice maximum has been low this year, meaning that there is less multi year ice and less drop to get to low minimums. However melt at the beginning of the seas has started off slow. Looking at the SST charts, the waters surround the ice are colder than than average helping slow melt from the edge https://psl.noaa.gov/map/clim/sst.shtml. The wind profile at the moment is blowing ice toward the European side to exit https://cryo.met.no/en/home, which compacts the ice area.
